<section id='Matter'>
    <h2><a href='#Matter'>The moral matter and its principle</a></h2>
    <p>
        The postulates are:
        </p>
    <dl>
        <dt><dfn>P1</dfn></dt>
        <dd>I value reason the most</dd>
        </dl>
    <dl>
        <dt><dfn>P2</dfn></dt>
        <dd>I think that all communications are limited to light speed</dd>
        </dl>
    <p>
        I'll explain what I mean by this value I place on reason.  First, I appreciate its steadfast work.
        Reason always works to find meaning and coherence in the world of experience,
        trying hard to fit each effect with its cause and each means with its end.
        <!--
        - reason informs my view of all things
            - whether looking backward or forward
            - nothing seems able to replace it
            -->
        It works diligently, trying all ways to make progress, never quitting one way except to try another.
        It is one of those rare things in life that I can safely rely on.  Or so I feel.
        </p>
    <p>
        I can also share in it.  I can experience reason working in me.
        I can even, on occaision, and with joy,
        <q>triumph o’er a secret wrung from nature’s close reserve</q>.<sup class='ref'>[<a href='#Bro55' id='Bro55qTG'>Bro55</a>]</sup>
        This makes me grateful to those in the past who carried reason forward with them,
        and hopeful for those in the future who, in their own capacity, may carry it further.
        </p>
    <p>
        But whatever my motive, however I came to value reason, I posit that I hold most tightly to it.
        I would do anything rather than see it fail or be diminished.
        </p>
    …
