<section id='Form'>
    <h2><a href='#Form'>Justifying the moral form by its material fitness</a></h2>
    <p>
        Here I make a practical argument in support of the two formal principles.
        I can’t offer a complete theory.  I don’t know whether it’s because I’m unskilled as a theoretician,
        or because the task is not proper to theory (or because my conclusions are ultimately wrong),
        but I’m unable to contrive a logical argument to derive the formal principles from the material.
        Regardless of their source, therefore, I begin simply by positing them: <sup class='ref'>[<a href='#SF' id='SF-a'>SF</a>]</sup>
        </p>
    <table class='proper'>
        <caption>Correlation of principles.</caption>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>form</td>
                <td>M2</td>
                <td>Promote a maximum, universal sum of personal freedom</td>
                    <!--
                    ( a maximum of personal freedom compatible with equal freedoms in general
                        -->
                <td>means</td>
                </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>form</td>
                <td>M1</td>
                <td>Relate personal action to an ultimate end</td>
                <td>means</td>
                </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>matter</td>
                <td>M0</td>
                <td>
                    I desire the endless continuity of rational being
                    that is made feasible by the limit of light speed
                    </td>
                <td>end</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    <p>
        Suppose (for sake of the argument) that M1 and M2 are introduced to modern society
        and made integral to its structure.  Whether by tradition, institution,
        private or public dissemination, their effects (imagine) are pervasive and strong.
        They’re a part of the social fabric.
        </p>
    <p>
        Later I’ll claim the feasibility of such an introduction.
        In this section, I claim only its fitness.
        I’ll argue that M1 and M2 together are exactly fit to the purpose of M0.
        Like a perfectly tailored suit [of formal wear|dress], nothing remains to be cut from the material
        and no obvious alteration would improve its fit.  (And it beats going naked.)
        This won’t prove, of course, that it’s the best possible suit [to wear] for the occaision.
        There may be other combinations of formal principles that exactly fit the purpose
        ([in the sense of] defying any easy alteration) and there may be one that better furthers it.
